==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wroth
<hw>Wroth</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>wroth</ets>,
<ets>wrap</ets>, AS. <ets>wr⟦amac⟧⟦edh⟧</ets> wroth, crooked, bad; akin
to <ets>wr⟦imac⟧⟦edh⟧an</ets> to writhe, and to OS.
<ets>wr⟦emac⟧⟦edh⟧</ets>angry, D. <ets>wreed</ets> cruel, OHG.
<ets>reid</ets> twisted, Icel. <ets>rei⟦edh⟧r</ets> angry, Dan. & Sw.
<ets>vred</ets>. See <er>Writhe</er>, and cf. <er>Wrath</er>.]</ety>
<def>Full of wrath; angry; incensed; much exasperated; wrathful.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Wroth</xex> to see his kingdom fail.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Revel and truth as in a low degree,⟦br⟧
They be full <qex>wroth</qex> [<it>i. e.</it>, at enmity] all day.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cain was very <qex>wroth</qex>, and his countenance fell.</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. iv. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wrought</ent>⟦br⟧
